data.title: Fork Forest

data.description:
WHAT IS FORK FOREST?

It is a ReFi initiative created late 2022 by members of Fork DAO¹. It was immediately embraced by the community and helped the DAO's growth. Though it acts a separate entity, there is love and collaboration. An active presence of the community can be seen in the sold out NFT collection for the first project, the ReFi topic in the DAO's Telegram group and the weekly Twitter/X Spaces in the DAO's account, therefore creating ReFi content in spanish. Fork Forest is currently collaborating with other ReFi projects such as Ekonavi and GainForest.

FORK FOREST 01

The first project FORK FOREST 01 was assembled in January 2023 and successfully completed in May². We supported a local organisation called 'Zapam Zucum' by providing means of financiation and tools to link them with the community. We set up an NFT collection³ and sold out. 100% of the money received at our first NFT campaign was directly dripped to 'Zapam Zucum'. We also onboarded 'Zapam Zupum' successfully⁴, so they could open a hot wallet and use the funds without depending on anyone else. Thanks to all the efforts, we succesfully planted 50 native trees in an open reunion with the community and even members of the DAO travelling to be part. Works of ecological conservation were part of the job. It all ended with a festival with local bands at sunset.

FORK FOREST 02

For this second project, we are addressing an important problem in Argentina: improper use of agrochemicals. We are addressing the same region as the first project⁵, bonding strongly with the local community.

The region is the Traslasierras Valley in the province of Cordoba, in Argentina. We are working with an Agricultural Engineer who's a High school teacher in a small town called Los Cerrilos. We met Ing. Fernando Parra in our first project, since we purchased native trees from his production. This town is suffering the consequences of the poor use of agrochemicals, and we intend to help.

The project is a 10km² forestal curtain mainly composed by native trees. Helped by the tools of GainForest, we can also measure all the benefits that a native forest brings to the world, and put value in a formerly forgotten area. 

We are aiming to cover the first of the three stages, the first of three stages of the forestal curtain. This will take place in mid september in a collaboration with the commune of Los Cerrillos⁶ and with the presence and support of INTA⁷ (Argentina's National Institute of Agricultural Technology). Detailed info is in the budget⁸.

data.problem: We address Climate change and Loss of biodiversity as whole problems, emmending with protection of native territory. We address our impact locally, where we face problems such as fires originated by humans, advance of real-state speculation, bad use of agrochemicals, lack of job opportunites, loss of native plants use and knowledge, and loss of traditional knowledge.
data.solution:
We are solving this problem by protecting certain areas and measuring the impact of mother nature's work. We also plant trees when necessary. 
We study and divulgate native knowledge, as you can see in our Podcast -it is in Spanish-.
Thanks to us measuring this, we help raise awareness and protection.
We hire local nurseries to buy the native trees, local services and artists and local tree-planters.
data.missionSummary: We are on a mission to protect native biodiversity, raise awareness and grow a local strong network of a Regen State. We do that by planting native trees and protecting native areas. The rest is the human work and human love around this mission.

data.title: GG19 - Climate Solutions
data.description: We are participating in Gitcoin Round 19 (GG19).

data.name: Gitcoin
data.description: Gitcoin creates solutions that empower digitally native communities to fund, build, and protect what matters.

data.title: GG18 - Climate Round
data.description: Grants in this round are primarily focused on climate solutions (the group may do other work, but the grant proposal must be directly related to climate solutions). The projects are explicitly helping to reduce GHGs, and/or serve as an important core infrastructure for web3 climate solution

We secured the money to buy the native trees for the last stage of the Living Wall thanks to Gitcoin Grants 20. It was easily our weakest Gitcoin Grant.

We had zero funding, a lot going on IRL but we tried anyways and made our contributions and received some as well. Dollars are so valued in Argentina that the small amount received was enough for us to buy the most important things.

So now we aim to fund a public event at spring this year.
data.title: Third stage of the Living Wall: almost ready!

data.description:
Second stage of the Living Wall at Los Cerrillos, Cordoba. As you can see in the description of our project, we are building a wall of native trees between the town of Los Cerillos and the potato fields that misuse agrochemicals and make the people sick. This is helping to raise awareness too.

Next and last stage is due at spring this year.

Check it out at.
